[SN]TITLE[SN]
Three men ordered to leave Shetland islands

[SN]FIRST-SENTENCE[SN]
Three men have been ordered to leave the Shetland islands following an alleged disturbance in Lerwick.

[SN]RESTBODY[SN]
Neil Barr, 33, from South Shields, Lee Donnelly, 40, from Jarrow, both in South Tyneside, and 33-year-old Michael Ward, from Pontefract in West Yorkshire, were granted bail.
Honorary Sheriff Willie Shannon said they must only return in connection with the court proceedings.
They denying behaving in a threatening or abusive manner.
'Walking around naked'
At Lerwick Sheriff Court, Mr Barr was accused of shouting, swearing, behaving aggressively, threatening a female member of staff, removing his clothes and walking around the Lounge Bar on Mounthooly Street naked.
Mr Barr is also charged with resisting, obstructing or hindering and struggling with three police officers in the town's Law Lane.
Mr Donnelly is alleged to have threatened a female member of staff.
Both Mr Donnelly and Mr Ward deny that they resisted, obstructed or hindered three police officers and attempted to release a man from custody at Law Lane.
Mr Donnelly and Mr Ward are also alleged to have shouted, sworn and acted aggressively.
